    name: `Panchase Waterfall`,
    category: "WATERFALL",
    summary: `Nestled within the Panchase Protected Forest above Pokhara, this seasonal waterfall tumbles through rhododendron-draped hillsides between Kaski, Parbat, and Syangja districts. The monsoon-fed cascade is best enjoyed as part of the popular Panchase Trek, rewarding hikers with mountain panoramas and verdant forest scenery.`,
    story: `<p>The Panchase region rises in a gentle arc of forested ridgelines to the south-west of Pokhara, its elevated forests feeding a web of streams and seasonal waterfalls that surge dramatically during the summer monsoon. The Panchase Waterfall, fed by the headwaters of the Harpan Khola — the river that ultimately fills the famous Phewa Lake — is one of these seasonal gems, best seen between June and October when the hillsides are alive with rushing water.</p><p>Panchase sits at the junction of Kaski, Parbat, and Syangja districts, a mid-mountain zone between 1,400 and 2,500 metres where subtropical forest gives way to temperate oak and rhododendron. In spring, those rhododendron groves are ablaze with red and pink blossoms; in monsoon, the waterfalls are at their loudest and most spectacular; in autumn, the forest turns to amber and gold with the Annapurna massif gleaming white beyond the ridgelines.</p><p>The short Panchase Trek, typically done in two or three days from Pokhara, passes through the forest and the waterfall zone, offering an accessible introduction to Himalayan trekking without the crowds of the Annapurna or Everest circuits. The trek usually begins in Bhumdi village after a short drive from Pokhara Lakeside. Along the route, trekkers pass through Gurung and Magar villages where traditional stone houses and communal chautaras are maintained with evident pride.</p><p>Panchase is a place that rewards those willing to look beyond Pokhara's famous lake-and-mountain postcards. The waterfall is not a singular dramatic plunge but rather a series of cascades descending through a narrow forest gorge, the sound of falling water mingling with birdsong in a forest that shelters numerous Himalayan bird species.</p>`,
