    category: "WATERFALL",
    summary: `Set in the cool hill station of Bhedetar on the border of Sunsari and Dhankuta districts, this scenic waterfall near the famous Namaste Falls area offers dramatic views of eastern Nepal's forested escarpment. The surrounding hills provide sweeping panoramas of the Himalaya including Kanchenjunga, Makalu, and Everest.`,
    story: `<p>Bhedetar occupies a privileged position in eastern Nepal's geography: a narrow ridge at 1,420 metres elevation perched where the Sunsari plains dramatically meet the hills of Dhankuta district, providing views in one direction over the vast Terai flatlands and in the other toward the icy ramparts of Kanchenjunga, Makalu, and Everest. The waterfall in the Bhedetar area descends through the forested hillside below this ridge, fed by the same catchment that gives the hill station its perpetually cool and misty atmosphere.</p><p>Just 16 kilometres north of Dharan, Bhedetar has long been a favourite weekend retreat for families from the Koshi zone cities, and the area around the waterfall is a popular picnic destination during the warmer months. The falls cascade through a narrow forested gorge before the water joins the streams descending toward the Koshi River basin below. The forest here is dense and relatively undisturbed, sheltering a rich bird community that includes several species endemic to the eastern Himalayan foothills.</p><p>The nearby Namaste Falls, eight kilometres further north on the same road, is perhaps more famous — its twin streams creating a silhouette resembling joined hands in the traditional Nepali greeting — but the Bhedetar waterfall offers its own charms without the increasing visitor numbers of its more celebrated neighbour. The monsoon months from June through September bring the falls to their most impressive volume, with mist rising through the canopy and the roar of water filling the gorge.</p><p>Bhedetar itself makes a pleasant stopover on any eastern Nepal itinerary, with its colonial-era feel, tea gardens, and the extraordinary mountain panoramas available on clear mornings before the clouds build from the south. The hill station is accessible by road from Dharan or Itahari, with regular public transport connections.</p>`,
    district: `Sunsari`,
    province: "KOSHI",
    lat: 26.92,
    lng: 87.26,
    elevation: 1380,
    entryFee: `Free`,
    bestSeason: `Jun–Sep, Oct–Nov`,
    openingHours: `Sunrise to sunset`,
    howToGetThere: `From Dharan, take a local bus or taxi north to Bhedetar (approx. 30 min, 16 km). From Bhedetar market, walk or take a short local vehicle toward the forested gorge area. Ask locals for directions to the nearest waterfall trail.`,
