    category: "WATERFALL",
    summary: `Near the famed Manakamana Goddess Temple in Gorkha, accessible by Nepal's first cable car, a cascade descends through the forested cliffs of the Marsyangdi valley. The waterfall adds a natural complement to one of Nepal's most visited pilgrimage sites, offering visitors a moment of natural reflection alongside their spiritual journey.`,
    story: `<p>The Manakamana Goddess Temple occupies a commanding ridge above the Marsyangdi River in Gorkha district, reached by Nepal's pioneering Manakamana Cable Car that has ferried millions of pilgrims up the steep hillside since 1998. The temple — dedicated to a manifestation of the goddess Bhagwati — is one of the most visited Hindu pilgrimage sites in Nepal, drawing devotees from across the country who come to have their wishes granted. In the forested cliffs and gorges surrounding the sacred ridge, seasonal waterfalls descend through the subtropical vegetation, their waters feeding the Marsyangdi below.</p><p>Manakamana Waterfall descends through the forested hillside adjacent to the cable car corridor, visible to passengers during the eight-minute gondola ride between Kurintar on the valley floor and the temple ridge above. The falls are particularly dramatic during the monsoon months when the Gorkha hills receive intense rainfall, the cascade swelling from a modest thread of water to a roaring white torrent that can be heard from the temple courtyard on stormy days.</p><p>The cable car base station at Kurintar sits on the Prithvi Highway, approximately 106 kilometres from Kathmandu and 102 kilometres from Pokhara, making Manakamana one of the most accessible major pilgrimage sites in Nepal. Most visitors focus entirely on the temple experience, but those who take time to explore the forested paths around the ridge discover a landscape of great natural beauty — ancient trees, flowering orchids, langur monkeys, and the constant backdrop of the Marsyangdi gorge far below.</p><p>The waterfall is best experienced from June through October during and after the monsoon, or in spring when the hillside vegetation is fresh and lush. The cable car operates from early morning until late afternoon, and pilgrimage visits naturally concentrate at festival times throughout the Hindu calendar.</p>`,
    district: `Gorkha`,
    province: "GANDAKI",
    lat: 27.93,
    lng: 84.59,
    elevation: 1300,
    entryFee: `NPR 1,120 return cable car ticket (foreigners), NPR 725 (Nepali citizens)`,
    bestSeason: `Jun–Oct, festival seasons year-round`,
    openingHours: `07:00–18:00 (cable car hours)`,
    howToGetThere: `From Kathmandu, drive or take a bus on the Prithvi Highway to Kurintar (approx. 3 hrs, 106 km). Take the Manakamana Cable Car up to the temple ridge (8-min ride). The waterfall is visible from the cable car and accessible via forest paths from the temple area.`,
