    name: `Kankrvitta Waterfall`,
    category: "WATERFALL",
    summary: `Near the border town of Kakkarbhitta in Jhapa district, seasonal waterfalls cascade through the Mechinagar hills above the busy India–Nepal border crossing. Set in the subtropical eastern Terai foothills, these cascades are a refreshing natural escape from the lowland heat, visited by travellers passing between Nepal and West Bengal.`,
    story: `<p>Kakkarbhitta — sometimes spelled Kakarbhitta — is Nepal's busiest eastern land border crossing with India, the gateway for travellers moving between Nepal and India's West Bengal state. The town sits in the flat subtropical plains of Jhapa district, and the surrounding landscape is characterised by the lush vegetation of the eastern Terai: sal forest, tea gardens, and cardamom plantations in the foothills that rise gently above the plains. Where these foothills are steep enough to create significant gradient, seasonal waterfalls form, and the Kankrvitta Waterfall is one such cascade hidden in the forested hills above the plains.</p><p>Jhapa is Nepal's easternmost district, sharing borders with India's Darjeeling and Sikkim regions. The district is one of Nepal's most prosperous, its lowland plains intensively cultivated with jute, sugarcane, and rice, while the foothills host tea gardens and cardamom plantations that generate substantial export income. The waterfall zone sits within these foothill forests, accessible from Kakkarbhitta by a short drive into the hills followed by a forest walk.</p><p>The Satakshi and Mechinagar areas of Jhapa have several seasonal waterfalls that are popular with domestic day-trippers from Jhapa and neighbouring Ilam district, particularly during the monsoon season when the falls are most active. The combination of cool forest air, the sound of rushing water, and the distant view of the Kanchenjunga range on clear days makes these hill excursions a welcome contrast to the lowland heat of the Jhapa plains.</p><p>Kakkarbhitta is easily accessible by road from Bhadrapur airport (30 min) or from Siliguri across the Indian border. The waterfall is best visited during or immediately after the monsoon from July through October. Local buses and shared vehicles connect Kakkarbhitta to the foothill villages above the town.</p>`,
