    name: `Roshi Waterfall`,
    category: "WATERFALL",
    summary: `Also known as Panchakanya Jharana, Roshi Waterfall in Kavrepalanchok cascades through a rocky gorge 40 kilometres east of Kathmandu near the historic town of Panauti. Crystal-clear water fills a natural swimming pool at the base of the falls, making it one of the closest and most refreshing natural bathing spots to the Nepali capital.`,
    story: `<p>Forty kilometres east of Kathmandu, beyond the Bhaktapur valley and the historic trading town of Banepa, the landscape opens into the rolling hills of Kavrepalanchok district. Here, near the ancient town of Panauti — one of Nepal's finest examples of medieval Newari urbanism, with its elaborate temple complex at the confluence of the Roshi and Punyamati rivers — the Roshi Waterfall (also called Panchakanya Jharana) cascades through a narrow gorge to fill a natural pool of exceptional clarity.</p><p>The waterfall is located in Roshi Rural Municipality, accessible via a short drive from Panauti and then a five-to-ten minute walk from the road. The Roshi River, from which the falls draw their name, is fed by the forested hills to the north and northeast of Kavrepalanchok, and its waters are clean enough to attract visitors specifically for swimming in the pool at the waterfall's base. This natural swimming hole is the waterfall's primary attraction during the warmer months — the cold mountain water providing perfect relief from Kathmandu's summer heat.</p><p>The route from Kathmandu to Roshi Waterfall passes through some of the most historically interesting terrain in the Bagmati zone: Bhaktapur with its UNESCO World Heritage Durbar Square, Banepa with its roadside temples, and finally Panauti, where the temple complex at the Triveni (sacred confluence) is considered one of the finest expressions of medieval Nepali religious architecture outside the Kathmandu Valley proper.</p><p>The monsoon season from July through September brings the waterfall to its most impressive volume, but the swimming pool is most popular from May through August when the water temperature is warmest. The drive from Kathmandu takes approximately 75 to 90 minutes by private vehicle, making this an ideal half-day excursion from the capital.</p>`,
