    name: `Solu Waterfall`,
    category: "WATERFALL",
    summary: `In the Solu region of Solukhumbu district — the lower, more forested half of Nepal's famous Everest region — waterfalls cascade through a landscape of ancient rhododendron forest, Buddhist monasteries, and traditional Sherpa and Rai villages. A natural highlight for trekkers approaching Everest via the classic overland route from Jiri.`,
    story: `<p>Solukhumbu district divides naturally into two distinct zones: Khumbu in the north, where the high Himalayan peaks rise above the glaciers that Everest expeditions navigate, and Solu in the south — a lower, warmer, more forested region where the Sherpa and Rai communities maintain traditional lifestyles in villages surrounded by ancient rhododendron and oak forest. The Solu Waterfall is a cascade in this lower region, fed by the numerous streams draining the Dudh Koshi and Likhu Khola watersheds that eventually join the Solu river system.</p><p>The classic approach to Everest Base Camp via the historic Hillary trail from Jiri passes through the Solu region, ascending gradually through this forested landscape before reaching the higher Khumbu zone. Along this route, waterfalls cascade from the steep hillsides — particularly impressive in the monsoon season when the combination of heavy rainfall and snowmelt from higher elevations pushes the mountain streams to their maximum capacity. The Solu Waterfall is one such cascade, its waters filling a natural pool that has historically served as a water source for the nearby village community.</p><p>The Solu region of Solukhumbu is less visited than the upper Khumbu, as most trekkers now fly directly to Lukla and bypass the lower hills entirely. This makes the Solu landscape one of the few remaining genuinely traditional trekking environments in the Everest region — the monasteries here are not yet overwhelmed with tourist traffic, the forests are intact, and the waterfalls flow through landscapes largely undisturbed by the development pressures affecting the Khumbu proper.</p><p>The district headquarters of Salleri is accessible by road from Kathmandu or by air to Phaplu airstrip (altitude 2,413 m), making the Solu region an increasingly practical destination for those who want an authentic Himalayan experience without the high-altitude acclimatisation requirements of the upper Khumbu.</p>`,
